'''Mangalore Anantha Pai''' (born 1931) is an Indian electrical engineer, academic and a Professor Emeritus at the [[University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign]].<ref name="The Year Book 2016">{{Cite web |url=http://www.insaindia.res.in/pdf/YearBook_2016.pdf |title=The Year Book 2016 |date=2016 |publisher=Indian National Science Academy}}</ref> A former professor of electrical engineering at the [[Indian Institute of Technology, Kanpur]],<ref name="List of Former Faculty">{{Cite web |url=http://www.iitk.ac.in/ee/former-faculty |title=List of Former Faculty |date=2016 |publisher=IIT Kanpur}}</ref> he is known for his contributions in the fields of power stability, power grids, large scale power system analysis, system security and optimal control of nuclear reactors<ref name="Brief Profile of the Awardee">{{Cite web |url=http://ssbprize.gov.in/Content/Detail.aspx?AID=320 |title=Brief Profile of the Awardee |date=2016 |publisher=Shanti Swarup Bhatnagar Prize |access-date=12 November 2016}}</ref> and he has published 8 books and several articles.<ref name="Faculty profile on University of Illinois">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ece.illinois.edu/directory/profile/mapai |title=Faculty profile on University of Illinois |date=2016 |publisher=University of Illinois}}</ref> Pai is the first India born scientist to be awarded a PhD in Electrical Engineering from the University of California, Berkeley.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}

Pai is an IEEE Life Fellow and is an elected fellow of the [[Indian National Science Academy]],<ref name="Indian fellow">{{Cite web |url=http://insaindia.res.in/detail.php?id=N80-0533 |title=Indian fellow |date=2016 |publisher=Indian National Science Academy}}</ref> [[Indian Academy of Sciences]],<ref name="Fellow profile">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ias.ac.in/describe/fellow/Pai,_Prof._Mangalore_Anantha |title=Fellow profile |date=2016 |publisher=Indian Academy of Sciences}}</ref> and Indian National Academy of Engineers<ref name="INAE fellows">{{Cite web |url=https://inae.in/search-of-fellows/ |title=INAE fellows |date=2016 |publisher=Indian National Academy of Engineers}}</ref>  and an elected and life fellow of the [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]]<ref name="IEEE Fellows Directory">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ieee.org/membership_services/membership/fellows/fellowsDirectory.html# |title=IEEE Fellows Directory |date=2016 |publisher=Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers}}</ref> The [[Council of Scientific and Industrial Research]], the apex agency of the Government of India for scientific research, awarded him the [[Shanti Swarup Bhatnagar Prize for Science and Technology]], one of the highest Indian science awards for his contributions to Engineering Sciences in 1974.<ref name="View Bhatnagar Awardees">{{cite web | url=http://ssbprize.gov.in/Content/AwardeeList.aspx | title=View Bhatnagar Awardees | publisher=Shanti Swarup Bhatnagar Prize | date=2016 | accessdate=12 November 2016}}</ref>{{Refn|group=note|Long link - please select award year to see details}}

== Biography ==

M. A. Pai. born on 5 October 1931 in the south Indian state of [[Karnataka]], did his graduate studies in electrical engineering at the [[University of Madras]] and after completing the course in 1953, started his career as an electrical engineer at the Electric Supply Department of [[Brihanmumbai Electric Supply and Transport]], then known as Bombay Electric Supply and Transport (BEST) Undertaking.<ref name="Indian fellow" /> After a service of 4 years, he moved to the US in 1957 where he completed his master's degree in electrical engineering (MS) at [[University of California, Berkeley]] in 1958 and continued at the institution to secure a PhD in 1961.<ref name="Register - University of California">{{cite book|title=Register - University of California|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-fo4AQAAMAAJ&pg=RA6-PA52|year=1958|publisher=University of California Press|pages=6–}}</ref> Subsequently, he joined the university as an assistant professor at [[University of California, Berkeley]]  (1961–62) before taking up Professorship at [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA) in 1962.<ref name="Faculty profile on University of California">{{Cite web |url=http://smartgrid.ucla.edu/about_people_af.html |title=Faculty profile on University of California |date=2016 |publisher=University of California Los Angeles}}</ref> At UCLA, he had the opportunity to work with [[Eliahu I. Jury]], a [[Rufus Oldenburger Medal|Rufus Oldenburger laureate]] on [[discrete time]] systems, and in 1963 he returned to India to join the Electrical Engineering department of the [[Indian Institute of Technology, Kanpur]] as an assistant professor.<ref name="List of Retired Faculty">{{Cite web |url=http://www.iitk.ac.in/dofa/data/alpha-faculty.pdf |title=List of Retired Faculty |date=2016 |publisher=IIT Kanpur}}</ref> He served the institute till 1981 during which period he held the positions of an associate professor from 1966 to 1969 and a professor thereafter till he went back to the US as a visiting professor at [[University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign]] in 1981.<ref name="Authors">{{Cite web |url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/6730699/ |title=Authors |date=2016 |publisher=IEEE Xplore}}</ref> He also had a stint as a consultant to the [[Uttar Pradesh Power Corporation Limited]] from 1971 to 1979. After two years of service as a visiting faculty at Illinois, he became a regular professor in 1983 and served out his academic career to superannuate in 2003.<ref name="Faculty profile on University of Illinois" /> In between, he also served as a visiting professor at the [[Memorial University of Newfoundland]] and [[Iowa State University]] and visited India on a [[Council of Scientific and Industrial Research|CSIR]]-[[UNDP]] program at [[Central Power Research Institute]]. Post-retirement, Illinois University made him an emeritus professor.<ref name="About the author">{{Cite web |url=https://books.google.ae/books?id=ZKzf_VtJfYcC&pg=PP4&lpg=PP4&dq=M+A+Pai+national+academy+of+sciences+India&source=bl&ots=_TaKTPNtIq&sig=AzNtW3S2JVQAAiruP9f4rfdhfOk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjtoIfUyrzRAhUZMlAKHfNjANMQ6AEILjAD#v=onepage&q=M%20A%20Pai%20national%20academy%20of%20sciences%20India&f=false |title=About the author |date=2016 |publisher=Tata McGraw-Hill Education}}</ref> He also serves as a consultant to [[Pacific Northwest National Laboratory]], advising them on ''Model Reduction and Dynamic Security of Power System''.<ref name="Faculty profile on University of California" />

== Legacy ==
Pai's early researches were based on power system stability, security and model reduction and his work on ''Model Reduction of Large-Scale Power Systems'' has been reported to be of significance to field of power systems.<ref name="About the author" /> He is known to have introduced [[Lyapunov stability|Lyapunov's method]] in researches on power system stability and energy functions.<ref name="Indian fellow" /> Introduction of computer applications in power systems is another of his contributions and a power system software he has developed is in use with several power distribution networks.<ref name="Handbook of Shanti Swarup Bhatnagar Prize Winners">{{cite web | url=http://www.csirhrdg.res.in/ssb.pdf | title=Handbook of Shanti Swarup Bhatnagar Prize Winners | publisher=Council of Scientific and Industrial Research | date=1999}}</ref> Later, he worked on [[Smart Grid]], [[Microgrid]] and [[Renewable Energy]] and how they could be integrated into the main [[electrical grid]] of a power system;<ref name="Faculty profile on University of California" /> earlier, at IIT Kanpur, he encouraged research on ''Control and Power''. He has also contributed in the field of industrial consultancy and has served as a member of the editorial boards of Power and Energy series of [[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]].<ref name="Faculty profile on University of California" />

In 1963, Pai was selected to join IIT Kanpur as one of the earliest member of the Electrical Engineering faculty. Under the guidance of economist John Kenneth Galbraith, IIT Kanpur became the first institute in India to offer Computer science education. The earliest computer courses were started at IIT Kanpur in August 1963 on an IBM 1620 system, which was flown from Princeton to Kanpur. The initiative for computer education came from the Electrical engineering department. An intense outreach program in Computer Education was established during his time at IIT Kanpur. It was during his years at IIT Kanpur, Pai published his first book, ''Computer Techniques in Power System Analysis''.<ref name="Pai1979">{{cite book|author=M. A. Pai|title=Computer Techniques in Power System Analysis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tFTgAAAACAAJ|year=1979|publisher=Tata McGraw-Hill|isbn=978-0-07-096551-5}}</ref> His second book, ''Power System Stability: Analysis by the Direct Method of Lyapunov'', was also published before he moved to US in 1981.<ref name="Pai1981">{{cite book|author=M. A. Pai|title=Power System Stability: Analysis by the Direct Method of Lyapunov|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=llrAQgAACAAJ|date=1 January 1981|publisher=North-Holland Publishing Company|isbn=978-0-444-86310-2}}</ref> This was followed by five more authored books, ''Com Tech In Power Sys Ana'',<ref name="Pai2005">{{cite book|author=Pai|title=Com Tech In Power Sys Ana|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZKzf_VtJfYcC|date=1 October 2005|publisher=Tata McGraw-Hill Education|isbn=978-0-07-059363-3}}</ref> ''Power System Dynamics and Stability'',<ref name="SauerPai2006">{{cite book|author1=Peter W. Sauer|author2=M. A. Pai|title=Power System Dynamics and Stability|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yWi9PAAACAAJ|year=2006|publisher=Stipes Publishing L.L.C.|isbn=978-1-58874-673-3}}</ref> ''Power Circuits and Electromechanics'',<ref name="Pai2010">{{cite book|author=M. A. Pai|title=Power Circuits and Electromechanics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NA67twAACAAJ|year=2010|publisher=Stipes Pub Llc|isbn=978-1-60904-009-3}}</ref> ''Energy Function Analysis for Power System Stability''<ref name="Pai2012">{{cite book|author=Anantha Pai|title=Energy Function Analysis for Power System Stability|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1HDgBwAAQBAJ|date=6 December 2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-1-4613-1635-0}}</ref> and ''Small Signal Analysis of Integrated Power Systems'', the last one published in 2016.<ref name="PaiPadiyar2016">{{cite book|author1=M. A. Pai|author2=K. R. Padiyar|title=Small Signal Analysis of Integrated Power Systems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S_ZRvgAACAAJ|date=28 June 2016|publisher=Alpha Science International Limited|isbn=978-1-78332-268-8}}</ref> In between, he co-edited an [[Oxford University Press]] [[festschrift]] on [[Homi J. Bhabha]] titled ''Homi Bhabha and the Computer Revolution'',<ref name="Homi Bhabha and the Computer Revolution">{{Cite book |url=https://www.amazon.com/Bhabha-Computer-Revolution-Edited-Shyamasundar/dp/0198072465 |title=Homi Bhabha and the Computer Revolution |last=R.K. Shyamasundar (Editor), M.A. Pai (Editor) |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0198072461 |editor-last=R.K. Shyamasundar, M.A. Pai |publication-date=2011 |page=300}}</ref> which was featured in the Indian edition of [[MIT Technology Review]] in May/June 2011.<ref name="Professor Emeritus Pai edits a book on computer pioneer Homi Bhabha">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ece.illinois.edu/newsroom/article/1298 |title=Professor Emeritus Pai edits a book on computer pioneer Homi Bhabha |date=2016 |publisher=University of Illinois}}</ref> He has also contributed chapters to books published by others<ref name="Chow2013">{{cite book|author=Joe H. Chow|title=Power System Coherency and Model Reduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KAVsXwAACAAJ|date=1 May 2013|publisher=Springer New York|isbn=978-1-4614-1802-3}}</ref><ref name="Savulescu2014">{{cite book|author=Savu Savulescu|title=Real-Time Stability in Power Systems: Techniques for Early Detection of the Risk of Blackout|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IdElBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA1|date=10 July 2014|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-319-06680-6|pages=1–}}</ref><ref name="Datta2012">{{cite book|author=Biswa Nath Datta|title=Applied and Computational Control, Signals, and Circuits: Recent Developments|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TV31BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA181|date=6 December 2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-1-4615-1471-8|pages=181–}}</ref> and has authored over 125 peer-reviewed articles;<ref name="List of articles">{{Cite web |url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/search/searchresult.jsp?searchWithin=%22Authors%22:.QT.M.%20A.%20Pai.QT.&newsearch=true |title=List of articles |date=2016 |publisher=IEEE Xplore}}</ref><ref name="On ResearchGate">{{Cite web |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Anantha_Pai |title=On ResearchGate |date=2016 |publisher=ResearchGate}}</ref> {{Refn|group=note|Please see ''Selected articles'' section}} the online article repository of Indian Academy of Sciences has listed 107 of them.<ref name="Browse by Fellow">{{Cite web |url=http://repository.ias.ac.in/view/fellows/Pai=3AMangalore_Anantha=3A=3A.html |title=Browse by Fellow |date=2016 |publisher=Indian Academy of Sciences}}</ref> He is reported to have helped organize two symposia of [[International Federation of Automatic Control]] in India and has delivered keynote or invited speeches at several science seminars in India and abroad including the Seminar on ''Voltage Instability in Power Network'' organized by the Delhi chapter of the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in 1991.<ref name="Voltage Instability in Power Network">{{Cite web |url=http://ewh.ieee.org/r10/delhi/MLIST91.htm |title=Voltage Instability in Power Network |date=2016 |publisher=IEEE Delhi}}</ref> He has also mentored a number of doctoral scholars in their studies.<ref name="Indian fellow" />

